.PD 0
.ie n .IP """my_strftime""" 4
.el .IP \f(CWmy_strftime\fR 4
.IX Xref "sv_strftime_tm my_strftime"
.IX Item "my_strftime"
.PD
These implement the libc \fBstrftime()\fR.
.Sp
On failure, they return NULL, and set \f(CW\*(C`errno\*(C'\fR to \f(CW\*(C`EINVAL\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`sv_strftime_tm\*(C'\fR is preferred, as it transparently handles the UTF\-8ness of
the current locale, the input \f(CW\*(C`fmt\*(C'\fR, and the returned result.  Only if the
current \f(CW\*(C`LC_TIME\*(C'\fR locale is a UTF\-8 one (and \f(CW\*(C`use\ bytes\*(C'\fR is not in effect)
will the result be marked as UTF\-8.
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`sv_strftime_tm\*(C'\fR takes a pointer to a filled-in \f(CW\*(C`struct\ tm\*(C'\fR parameter.  It
ignores the values of the \f(CW\*(C`wday\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`yday\*(C'\fR fields in it.  The other fields
give enough information to accurately calculate these values, and are used for
that purpose.
.Sp
The caller assumes ownership of the returned SV with a reference count of 1.
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`my_strftime\*(C'\fR is kept for backwards compatibility.  Knowing if its result
should be considered UTF\-8 or not requires significant extra logic.
.Sp
The return value is a pointer to the formatted result (which MUST be arranged
to be FREED BY THE CALLER).  This allows this function to increase the buffer
size as needed, so that the caller doesn't have to worry about that, unlike
libc \f(CWstrftime()\fR.
.Sp
The \f(CW\*(C`wday\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`yday\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`isdst\*(C'\fR parameters are ignored by \f(CW\*(C`my_strftime\*(C'\fR.
Daylight savings time is never considered to exist, and the values returned for
the other two fields (if \f(CW\*(C`fmt\*(C'\fR even calls for them) are calculated from the
other parameters, without need for referencing these.
.Sp
Note that both functions are always executed in the underlying
\&\f(CW\*(C`LC_TIME\*(C'\fR locale of the program, giving results based on that locale.
.RS 4
.Sp
.Vb 4
\& SV *    sv_strftime_tm(SV *fmt, const struct tm *mytm)
\& char *  my_strftime   (const char *fmt, int sec, int min,
\&                        int hour, int mday, int mon, int year,
\&                        int wday, int yday, int isdst)
.Ve
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
